description:
The Semantic Logging Application Block provides a set of destinations (sinks) to persist application events published using a subclass of the EventSource class from the System.Diagnostics.Tracing namespace. Sinks include Windows Azure table storage, SQL Server databases, and rolling files with several formats and you can extend the block by creating your own custom formatters and sinks. For the those sinks that can store structured data, the block preserves the full structure of the event payload in order to facilitate analyzing or processing the logged data.
      An out-of-proc Windows Service is available as a separate download from http://go.microsoft.com/fwlink/p/?LinkID=290903.
      This application block is a part of Microsoft Enterprise Library 6.0.
summary: The Semantic Logging Application Block provides a set of destinations (sinks) to persist application events published using a subclass of the EventSource class.

		To create a user account and obtain these credentials, please visit signere.no .

Inspired by the recent development in the area of CQRS and DDD-implementation techniques, this framework allow you to implement custom message handlers that can be automatically registered at startup time with your MessageHandlerFactory of choice. It basically takes off the burden of some infrastructural concerns while demanding absolutely no design-choices for your own code, except for implementing certain interfaces where required.

The Unity-dependency is only present because the framework comes with a default MessageHandlerFactory implemented for Unity, but you can remove or replace this dependency when implementing your custom factory.
summary: Contains a small framework that lets you implement your application in a Message-Oriented fashion.

The Unity-dependency is only present because the framework comes with a default MessageHandlerFactory implemented for Unity, but you can remove or replace this dependency when implementing your custom factory.

Welcome to Academy Collections.

As result of a deep research, Academy.Collections presents new data structures implementations that expands your boundaries when using Microsoft .NET Framework. The objects implementations and the structure of the library is presented in need-order instead of a group of data structures categories, this way the name of the collections and methods (what an end user interacts with) provides better suggestion of its functionalities.

The collections implemented do not belong to a deep-inheritance group of base collections, but integrate to the Microsoft .NET Framework collections interfaces plus other new (well integrated) interfaces. This way the dependencies are minimized and the collections performance grows to its best.

In Academy.Collections you will not find any collection contained in the Microsoft .NET Base Class Library (System.Collections namespaces), those are pretty good implementations. This library tries to present new features through a group of innovative collections using similar names, descriptions and concepts that Microsoft did in the Microsoft .NET Framework BCL Collections. This way your code experience will be as intuitive as always has been.
summary: Your code experience is naturally improving while using Microsoft .NET. Try Academy.Collections and enjoy new versatile and confortable collections for Microsoft .NET Framework 4.5.

The PayPal Core SDK addresses the essential needs of the PayPal API caller:
Frequent and up-to-date releases: The PayPal Core SDK is available on NuGet, which translates as immediate SDK refreshes upon updates to PayPal APIs.
Simpler configuration: A single configuration file that lets you manage your API credentials (supports multiple credentials), connectivity details, and service endpoints.
Error log: The PayPal Core SDK uses the log4net tool to log output statements to a text file to help locate the problem.
Backward compatibility: The PayPal Core SDK developed in .NET Framework 2.0 should compile on later versions of the .NET Framework.
